Step 1 Read a Managed Policy First
#############
{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": [
                "s3:Get*",
                "s3:List*",
                "s3:Describe*",
                "s3-object-lambda:Get*",
                "s3-object-lambda:List*"
            ],
            "Resource": "*"
        }
    ]
}
###################
AWS IAM Policy 
This is an AWS IAM (Identity and Access Management) policy that controls permissions to AWS S3 resources. Here's a line-by-line breakdown:

Top-Level Structure
json"Version": "2012-10-17"
The policy language version. 2012-10-17 is the current and recommended version — it's a fixed date string AWS uses to identify the policy syntax version, not an expiration date.

json"Statement": [ ... ]
An array that holds one or more permission rules. Each object inside is a separate rule.

Inside the Statement
json"Effect": "Allow"
Determines whether the actions are permitted or denied. Here it's Allow, meaning everything listed below is granted. The only other option is "Deny".

json"Action": [
    "s3:Get*",
    "s3:List*",
    "s3:Describe*",
    "s3-object-lambda:Get*",
    "s3-object-lambda:List*"
]
The specific AWS API operations being permitted. The * is a wildcard that matches anything:
ActionWhat it permitss3:Get*All S3 read operations — GetObject, GetBucketPolicy, GetEncryptionConfiguration, etc.s3:List*List buckets, list objects within buckets — ListBucket, ListAllMyBuckets, etc.s3:Describe*Any S3 describe-type calls (limited set, mostly metadata)s3-object-lambda:Get*Read operations through S3 Object Lambda (modified object responses via Lambda functions)s3-object-lambda:List*List operations through S3 Object Lambda access points

json"Resource": "*"
Defines which AWS resources this policy applies to. The * wildcard means all S3 buckets and objects in the account — no restrictions by bucket name, prefix, or ARN.

Summary

This is a read-only S3 policy. It grants the ability to read and list any object in any S3 bucket, but grants no write, delete, or modify permissions (Put*, Delete*, Create* are all absent).

It's commonly attached to roles for auditing, data analytics, or backup tools that need to read S3 data without modifying it.
